{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox prepared food | name = Fasolada | image = Fasolada.JPG | image_size = 250px | caption = | alternate_name = Fasoulada, fasoulia | region = [[Cyprus]], [[Egypt]], [[Greece]], [[Iraq]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Lebanon]], [[Libya]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Sudan]], [[Syria]], [[Turkey]] and [[Yemen]] | creator = | course = | type = [[Soup]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Common bean|Dry white beans]], [[olive oil]], [[vegetable]]s | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''Fasolada''', '''fasoulada''' or sometimes '''fasolia''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: فاصوليا), ({{lang-el|φασολάδα, φασουλάδα or φασόλια}}) is a [[Greek cuisine|Greek]], Levantine, and [[Cypriot cuisine|Cypriot]] [[soup]] of [[Common bean|dry white beans]], [[olive oil]], and vegetables, sometimes called the "national food of the [[Greeks]]".<ref>Λεξικό της κοινής Νεοελληνικής, 1998</ref>
Its counterpart in [[Turkish cuisine]] is called '''[[kuru fasulye]]'''. The [[Arab cuisine|Arabic]] version is called '''fasoulia''' ({{lang-ar|فاصوليا}}) and is found in [[Egypt]], [[Iraq]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Lebanon]], [[Libya]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Sudan]], [[Syria]], and [[Yemen]].
Fasolada is made by simmering beans with tomatoes and other vegetables such as [[carrots]], [[onion]], [[parsley]], [[celery]], and [[bay leaf]]. [[Lima beans]] are sometimes used instead of white beans. Recipes vary considerably.
It is often enriched with [[olive oil]] either in the kitchen or on the table.
Unlike the [[Italian cuisine|Italian]] ''fagiolata'', the [[Brazilian cuisine|Brazilian]] and [[Portuguese cuisine|Portuguese]] ''[[feijoada]]'', [[Romanian cuisine|Romanian]] ''fasole'' and the [[Spanish cuisine|Spanish]] ''[[fabada]]'', fasolada does not contain meat.
