[[File:Tire Machèt.jpg|thumb|Tire machèt – Cap Rouge, Haiti]] '''''Tire machèt''''' ("pull [the] [[machete]]") is a [[Haiti]]an [[martial art]]; a form of [[fencing]] with machetes.
The origin of the practice lies in the [[Haitian Revolution]] of 1791-1804, in which rebel slaves, many armed only with the machetes they had used to cut [[sugarcane]], defeated the French colonial army. ''Tire machèt'' combines elements of historical European fencing and traditional African combat systems.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poon|first1=Linda|title='En Garde' Takes On New Urgency In A Duel With Machetes|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/01/24/379333823/en-garde-takes-on-new-urgency-in-a-duel-with-machetes|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=NPR.org|language=en}}</ref> It is traditionally practiced in secret.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Buder|first1=Emily|title=The Master of a Secret Machete Martial Art|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/video/index/545057/papa-machete/|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=The Atlantic|date=6 November 2017}}</ref>
Haitian master fencer Alfred Avril (d. 2014) was among the first to open up his practice to the world, through a 10-year collaboration with Reginald Turnier and Michael Dylan Rogers of the Haitian Machete Fencing Project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fusion.net/story/5681/papa-machete-film-preserves-the-art-of-haitian-machete-fencing/|title='Papa Machete' Film Preserves the Art of Haitian Machete Fencing|last=Castillo|first=Arielle|date=19 May 2014|work=Fusion|access-date=2018-01-08|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=30636275|title=Grace, danger blend in Haiti's machete fighting|last=McFadden|first=David|date=9 July 2014|work=|access-date=2018-01-08|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> A 2014 documentary short film by Jonathan David Kane, ''Papa Machete'', depicted Alfred Avril training his sons and other students.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|last1=Morgenstern|first1=Hans|title="You are completely winded, and then you take a swig of rum:" Jonathan David Kane On Papa Machete|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/you-are-completely-winded-and-then-you-take-a-swig-of-rum-jonathan-david-kane-on-papa-machete-6498988|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=Miami New Times|date=17 December 2014}}</ref>
